## v1.1.0 — 2026-06-19

**Changed by:** Odysseus session 2026-06-19 — SECOND `/learn` for the same topic. The
R0 plan (v1.0.0, PR #2590) was NOGO'd by a reviewer and REVISED; this entry captures
the revision's learnings.

**Verification:** `unverified` (plan was reviewed, not run end-to-end; no
`nats-server -t` parse check and no functional auth test were executed this session)

### What changed

- Added 6 new durable findings to Results & Parameters / Proposed Workflow:
  1. `verify_and_map` does NOT match a bare CN. Mapping order is SAN-email → SAN-DNS →
     full RFC-2253 Subject DN. The v1.0.0 `# CN=hermes.homeric` mapping would have
     matched NOTHING and rejected every client — the #1 reviewer NOGO. FIX: carry a
     DNS SAN per role (`<role>.homeric`) and set `accounts.users[].user` to that exact
     SAN-DNS string; document full-DN only as a discouraged fallback; pin the
     convention in the ADR so cert issuance and config stay in lockstep.
  2. Fail-closed auth breaks every plaintext client — enumerate them from real service
     code, not just `e2e/`. On-disk: Hermes `config.py:34`, Telemachy `config.py:21`,
     `docker-compose.crosshost.yml:45` all default to `nats://`.
  3. Distinguish mTLS-capable-but-unconfigured vs needs-code per client. Hermes already
     has `build_ssl_context()` + cert fields (config, not code). Telemachy has a
     `require_tls` gate but NO client-cert wiring (a genuine code gap → follow-up issue).
  4. The stream-creator account (Hermes, ADR-005) is highest blast-radius — its cert is
     a hard runbook prerequisite before enabling `verify_and_map`, else no streams.
  5. Grep-for-token verification is insufficient for a security change — add functional
     tests: no-cert connect refused, stream-creator can create a stream, low-priv cert
     denied a subtree.
  6. JetStream per-account grants are easy to under-scope (`$JS.API.CONSUMER.>` +
     `$JS.API.STREAM.INFO.>` + `$JS.ACK.>`); validate functionally, don't assert blindly.
- Added 4 new Failed Attempts rows (bare-CN mapping; grep-only-e2e; assume-all-need-code;
  token-grep verification).
- Updated the uncertain-assumptions list to record SAN-DNS mapping as the top
  still-unverified risk plus the `--san` / step-ca flag uncertainty.
- Bumped version 1.0.0 → 1.1.0 (MINOR: new findings + new failed-attempts rows, same
  topic, same unverified level). Updated date.

### Why

The R0 plan's cert→user mapping was wrong: `verify_and_map` never matches a bare CN, so
the proposed `accounts{}` would have rejected 100% of clients. The reviewer also flagged
that the downstream-breakage check only grepped `e2e/tools/justfile`, missing the real
service clients that default to plaintext `nats://` and would fail closed. Finally,
token-presence greps cannot prove auth is actually enforced. These revisions make the
plan implementable: SAN-DNS mapping convention, full client enumeration, capable-vs-code
triage, and functional acceptance tests.

